sentences: Giorgos Hatzinasios (also spelled Hadjinasios; Greek: Γιώργος Χατζηνάσιος, pronounced [ˈʝoɾɣos xadziˈnasios]; born 19 January 1942) is a Greek songwriter and composer.
Since 1972, he has achieved much recognition in Greece and abroad and his more than forty albums, some amongst which have received gold and platinum status.
Hatzinasios wrote the music for and conducted Greece's entry, "Mathima Solfège", in the Eurovision Song Contest 1977.
He won an award in the 1980 Rose d'Or with the song 'Όταν γύρω Νυχτώνει' ('When Night Falls Around').
The oratorio was performed again at Mystras in 2007 with the Greek Radio Symphony Orchestra and Chorus participating.
In 2005, the first performance of his cantata Ωδή στον Μέγα Αλέξανδρο ('Ode to Alexander the Great') took place at the Athens Concert Hall.
He was a candidate for Greece's entry in the Eurovision Song Contest 2010 with the song "Illusion".
The song was performed by Pascalis, Marianna, Robert & Bessy and finished fifth on the night.
He won an award in the 1980 Rose d'Or with the song 'Όταν γύρω Νυχτώνει' ('When Night Falls Around').
Hatzinasios gave the world premiere of his Byzantine-themed oratorio Χρονικόν της Αλώσεως ('Chronicle of the Fall').
He now works in shipping and lives in Monaco.
